{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584439"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:46:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:46:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14520"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14520"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.19,0.15,0.23,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7215"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7215"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95981"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6655"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21668"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe abdominal aorta gives rise to several branches that supply either visceral organs or parietal (body wall) structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies parietal structures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subcostal artery","Anterior intercostal artery","Medial sacral artery","Inferior phrenic artery","Superior mesenteric artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial sacral artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a small, unpaired branch arising from the posterior aspect of the abdominal aorta just superior to its bifurcation. It descends in the midline to supply parietal structures including the lower lumbar vertebrae, sacrum, and coccyx.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubcostal artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the thoracic (not abdominal) aorta. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior intercostal artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the internal thoracic artery, not the abdominal aorta. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior phrenic artery\u003C/strong\u003E, while a branch of the abdominal aorta, supplies the diaphragm which is not considered a parietal structure. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a visceral branch supplying the midgut derivatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main parietal branches of the abdominal aorta are the lumbar arteries (typically four pairs) and the medial sacral artery. These vessels supply the vertebral column, spinal cord, and posterior body wall structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The medial sacral artery is an unpaired branch from the posterior abdominal aorta that supplies the sacrum and coccyx.","Parietal branches of the abdominal aorta supply the body wall and vertebral column.","The main parietal branches of the abdominal aorta are the lumbar arteries and medial sacral artery."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Shahoud JS, Miao JH, Bolla SR. Anatomy, Thorax, Heart Aorta. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538140/","Jacob, S. (2007). Human anatomy: a clinically-orientated approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Chenin L, Tandabany S, Foulon P, Havet E, Peltier J. A median sacral artery anterior to the iliocaval junction: a case report-anatomical considerations and clinical relevance for spine surgery. Surg Radiol Anat. 2018 Jan;40(1):115-117. doi: 10.1007/s00276-017-1917-9. Epub 2017 Sep 5. PMID: 28875294."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95981"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14520"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95981"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T16:20:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T16:20:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7215"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113966"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","l